The Kubernetes Crusade: Workshop on Defending & Attacking Kubernetes

Lab: Cilium

Star Wars Demo

If current working directory is not workspace/.

  • Click on + icon, then select new terminal to open new terminal.

  • Keep current working directory as workspace/
cd course/7_protection_strategies/7.5_cilium/
ls

In the following Star Wars-inspired example, there are three microservice applications: deathstar, tiefighter, and xwing.

  • Check the status of the daemonset cilium.
kubectl rollout status -n kube-system daemonset/cilium

Now let's deploy a simple empire demo application. It is made of several microservices, each identified by Kubernetes labels:

  • the Death Star: org=empire, class=deathstar
  • the Imperial TIE fighter: org=empire, class=tiefighter
  • the Rebel X-Wing: org=alliance, class=xwing

The deployment also includes a deathstar-service, which load-balances traffic to all pods with label org=empire, class=deathstar.

  • Deploy the demo application by running.
kubectl apply -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/cilium/cilium/HEAD/examples/minikube/http-sw-app.yaml

  • Verify that the pods and services are running.
kubectl get pods,svc

Each pod will also be represented in Cilium as an Endpoint. To retrieve a list of all endpoints managed by Cilium, the Cilium Endpoint (or cep) resource can be used.

  • List all endpoints managed by Cilium (ciliumendpoint).
kubectl get cep --all-namespaces

  • Death Star access
  • From the perspective of the deathstar service, only the ships with label org=empire are allowed to connect and request landing!

Network Access

  • To simulate our connectivity tests, we will be executing simple API calls using curl by landing our TIE fighter on the Death Star.

The command above lets us get a shell on the tiefighter pod and run a HTTP POST request to the deathstar Service to request landing.

  • Get a shell on the tiefighter pod.
kubectl exec tiefighter -- curl -s -XPOST deathstar.default.svc.cluster.local/v1/request-landing

  • Now test if the X-wing can access the Death Star.
kubectl exec xwing -- curl -s -XPOST deathstar.default.svc.cluster.local/v1/request-landing

The rebel alliance X-wing can access to the DeathStar which should not be allowed, this represents that the security policy is missing.

Identities and Cloud Native

Kubernetes pods, which are ephemeral and dynamically scheduled, are frequently assigned IP addresses that change over time.

Cilium, rather than using IP addresses, Cilium leverages the labels assigned to pods to define security policies.

Creating Network Policy
  • Problem:
  • Restrict deathstar landing requests to the ships that have label org=empire only, match on empire ships only.
spec:
  description: "Restrict deathstar access to empire ships"
  endpointSelector:
    matchLabels:
      org: empire
      class: deathstar
  • Ingress from endpoints with the label empire should be allowed to port 80 for protocol tcp.
Enforcing Network Policy
  • Apply the policy to the cluster.
kubectl apply -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/cilium/cilium/HEAD/examples/minikube/sw_l3_l4_policy.yaml

  • Land the empire tiefighter again (HTTP POST from tiefighter to deathstar on the /v1/request-landing path).
  • Get a shell on the tiefighter pod.
kubectl exec tiefighter -- curl -s -XPOST deathstar.default.svc.cluster.local/v1/request-landing

  • In comparison, try to request landing from the xwing pod & see that the request will eventually time out.

  • Get a shell on the xwing pod.

Kill the request with Ctrl+C once it stuck.

kubectl exec xwing -- curl -s -XPOST deathstar.default.svc.cluster.local/v1/request-landing

Successfully blocked access to the deathstar from an X-Wing ship.

Tighter Rules

  • As of now, it was sufficient to either deny tiefighter/xwing access to the deathstar's API completely or completely grant them access. However, do not rely on the thousands of tiefighter pilots throughout the entire empire?
  • Each service that calls deathstar’s API should be limited to making only the set of HTTP requests it requires.
  • The deathstar service exposes some maintenance APIs which should not be called by random empire ships. To see why those APIs are sensitive, run:
  • Get a shell on the tiefighter pod.
kubectl exec tiefighter -- curl -s -XPUT deathstar.default.svc.cluster.local/v1/exhaust-port

Unauthorized access such as above can have adverse security repercussions. Hence enforce the policies on the HTTP layer, at layer 7, to limit what exact APIs the tiefighter is allowed to call.

  • Extend the existing policy with an HTTP rule such as, This will restrict API access to only the /v1/request-landing path and will thus prevent users from accessing the /v1/exhaust-port, which caused a crash.
rules:
  http:
  - method: "POST"
    path: "/v1/request-landing"
  • Verify in the Kubernetes manifest that this policy will filter access to the deathstar by path.
apiVersion: "cilium.io/v2"
kind: CiliumNetworkPolicy
metadata:
  name: "rule1"
spec:
  description: "L7 policy to restrict access to specific HTTP call"
  endpointSelector:
    matchLabels:
      org: empire
      class: deathstar
  ingress:
  - fromEndpoints:
    - matchLabels:
        org: empire
    toPorts:
    - ports:
      - port: "80"
        protocol: TCP
      rules:
        http:
        - method: "POST"
          path: "/v1/request-landing"
  • Apply the updated policy to the cluster.
kubectl apply -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/cilium/cilium/HEAD/examples/minikube/sw_l3_l4_l7_policy.yaml

  • Run the same test as above, and see the different outcome:
kubectl exec tiefighter -- curl -s -XPUT deathstar.default.svc.cluster.local/v1/exhaust-port

Cleanup

# Remove the Network Policy
kubectl delete -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/cilium/cilium/HEAD/examples/minikube/sw_l3_l4_policy.yaml

# Delete the deployed application
kubectl delete -f https://raw.githubusercontent.com/cilium/cilium/HEAD/examples/minikube/http-sw-app.yaml
